I have full confidence PLTR will have great earnings but Im just a person. If you sell, what do you plan to do with the money? Buy another stock, hold cash, or pull the profit for use? Id say take some profits 50 instead of 100 profit and let some of your gains also work for you. If your sentiment toward the stock hasnt changed, and you feel it will continue to ascend, theres no real reason to pull the money due to an arbitrary number. If you didnt sell at 25, 50, etcetera, and you still believe in the stock then I see no reason to pull the money. People on here constantly kick themselves for selling a stock too early. No need to reflect back one day this is all theoretical and say I lost out on 400 profit because I sold at 100. If you have confidence but want to be more risk averse then sell some. If you can see PLTR at 100 in the futurenear future, keep it where it is. Currently over 400 with NVDA and Ive had no plans yet to sell. I see PLTR going on a similar path. Until news indicates otherwise its not the worst place to keep your money parked. You could look at putting profits in a less volatile sector. Its easy to be in a tech heavy sector because the money comes fast when it does, so do the losses. You could look at other stocks that guard against rapid deceleration and volatility when the day comes that tech stocks slow down and market corrections occur. Just trying to provide different outlooks to your good problem.

PLTR Position ideas with 100 Gains 1 COLLAR your gains Sell Calls that are 1020 OTM 5060 and use the premium to purchase Puts You still get 10 upside appreciation, but protect yourself against a steep selloff if Earnings are bad 2 Sell 100200 shares here 44.86, Sell 12x 50 Calls for Earnings, and then sell 13 CashSecured Puts CSP down under 35. This gives you realized profits now and will improve your cost basis by 10 if earnings go bad. This works since you dont need the money for a few years. 3 Sell 400 shares here 44.86 Sell some further dated CSP cashsecured puts buy 1x or 2x lotto calls for upside exposure if they hit Earnings and push over 5560. RECYCLE PROFITS is the long game!!

Sell half hold half is one way to do it, the other one is to sell OTM leaps. Stock is trading 45 right now. You can get 6 per contract or 600 per contract for selling a January 2026 65 call. On 500 shares you would bring in 3,000 right now and if your options get hit and exercised, great you sell the shares at 65. If the shares are not at that price at that time you just keep the money. If you plan on holding longterm this is one of my favorite strategies because it bakes in a further 50 appreciation from where you are and you get paid for doing it

PLTR has potential to have a staircase earnings. So using PE ratio isnt really a good way to value the company in the coming 15 years. If you feel it PE ratio is too high you are free to sell and buy something else. For myself I am holding. My cost basis is 11.

PE isnt a great metric for PLtR as they fairly recently turned profitable. Ao their earnings are still a relatively small percentage of revenue but growing faster than revenue. So what you will likely see is PE ratio decreasing over time. Unless share price grows faster than earnings growth. So lets say over next 5 years revenue doubles. But earnings quadruples. If the share price quadruples, PE stays flat. If share price triples, PE drops even though revenue doubled.
High PEs tend to go higher and low PEs tend to go lower.

the index funds dont buy it all at once... True. The index funds that use physical sampling do not have to buy the exact amount of a stock that its market cap suggests, they can ignore some stocks entirely or buy only a smaller amount of it, and buy it over the course of a few days. As long as the overall performance of their portfolio is in line with the index. The difference between the index and the funds holdings is called tracking difference. The tracking difference is usually very small, so the leeway the funds have is low, there is a high likelihood some funds will buy PLTR.

If you are worried about a market downturn and ready to make drastic moves to protect your money based on a fear of a crash this means one simple thing. You are invested way above risk tolerance that leads to rather poor decisionmaking My advise is create a portfolio you are comfortable with , this usually means allocating to some portion of bonds. And yes this will drag performance down in bull markets but hopefully you wont be tempted to do something very dumb like allocate 25 of your fund to a short fund. Also holding a long and short fund at the same time makes zero sense , in your 2 you would be net short on the market by 25 . If you really wanted to do this it would make more sense to just be 92 money market and 8 SQQQ Basically my advise is to create a portfolio something like 75 equities 25 bonds or what ever you are comfortable with and dont make drastic changes, slowly balance more to bonds as you age or approach retirement However going from 100 equities to basically 75 cash and 25 short is a drastic change that will most likely backfire.

Ill give you a serious answer though that may help you understand... Lets say that PLTR trades flat everyday all the way to contract expiration date. Every single day your cons will decrease in value even though the stocks not moving. If PLTR stock went down by a 0.10 to 0.15 everyday for the next two months or more, You lose money. If PLTR goes up in the same increments you make slightly more money. So in 2 of those 3 scenarios you lose money... see what Im getting at? So the most likely outcome of every options trade is 33.3 chance you win and a 66.6 you will lose. It gets more technical but for your current situation these are your odds now. Ideally if you have 2 cons you would sell 1 and let the other run. In the case of a 100 trade absolutely sell one and play with house money. Now you cant lose. In your case you have 3 and you have achieved 200 which puts you way above average market investment returns. So you should sell 2 cons and basically lock in a 100 trade and see how much higher PLTR goes. If your runner drops to 50 sell it and lock in 150 gains and be happy. If it continues up just move the goal post higher till it drops and touches it. Just my advice

Like when I say sometimes it makes sense to exercise, Im probably talking less than 1 of the time.

Are your goals to exercise for the shares, or sell the calls to turn a profit? As you get closer to expiration those options are going to lose value so if youre wanting to just make cash from them then youre probably better off selling then sooner rather than later.

The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration FAA is preparing to release a crucial regulation that will help pave the way for the commercialization of eVTOL aircraft in the U.S., according to Christopher Coes, acting under secretary of transportation for policy at the U.S. Department of Transportation. Speaking at Honeywells Advanced Air Mobility AAM Summit on Sept. 19, Coes announced that the final special federal aviation regulation SFAR for poweredlift pilot certification and operations is expected to be published in the next month.

Update 2 This information is huge regarding final SFAR FAA Rule The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration FAA is preparing to release a crucial regulation that will help pave the way for the commercialization of eVTOL aircraft in the U.S., according to Christopher Coes, acting under secretary of transportation for policy at the U.S. Department of Transportation. Speaking at Honeywells Advanced Air Mobility AAM Summit on Sept. 19, Coes announced that the final special federal aviation regulation SFAR for poweredlift pilot certification and operations is expected to be published in the next month. I think youll see it is quite responsive to industry comments, Coes told attendees. It will come well ahead of certifications that the FAA is working very hard with our manufacturers. The SFAR was a hot topic at last years summit, where the draft version faced considerable criticism. Industry concerns focused on the certification process for pilots, the requirement for dual flight controls, energy reserves for electric aircraft, and flight simulation training devices. Many in the industry felt the rules governing pilot certification and operations of a novel technology like poweredlift eVTOLs should be modernized to reflect the unique aspects of electrification and range. However, at this years summit, the mood had shifted toward cautious optimism for the release of the final SFAR. Theres great anticipation for the rule, which were told is coming in just a few weeks, said Kristie Greco Johnson, senior vice president of government affairs with the National Business Aviation Association NBAA. If the FAA can deliver the rule in just a few short weeks, itll be a major accomplishment for the agency. While Coes contends the final SFAR will be released in the next month, the FAA technically has until Dec. 16 to finalize the regulation, according to the FAA reauthorizaton bill. The same bill also mandated that a notice of proposed rulemaking NPRM for unmanned aerial systems UAS operating beyond visual line of sight BVLOS be issued by Sept. 16. However, the FAA missed that deadline, raising concerns about the SFARs timely release. There is broad consensus that the U.S. faces stiff competition from global players to lead in AAM. With first movers like Joby Aviation and Archer Aviation aiming for a 2025 commercialization of eVTOLs, the pressure is on the FAA to meet expectations.

The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration FAA is preparing to release a crucial regulation that will help pave the way for the commercialization of eVTOL aircraft in the U.S., according to Christopher Coes, acting under secretary of transportation for policy at the U.S. Department of Transportation. Speaking at Honeywells Advanced Air Mobility AAM Summit on Sept. 19, Coes announced that the final special federal aviation regulation SFAR for poweredlift pilot certification and operations is expected to be published in the next month. I think youll see it is quite responsive to industry comments, Coes told attendees. It will come well ahead of certifications that the FAA is working very hard with our manufacturers. The SFAR was a hot topic at last years summit, where the draft version faced considerable criticism. Industry concerns focused on the certification process for pilots, the requirement for dual flight controls, energy reserves for electric aircraft, and flight simulation training devices. Many in the industry felt the rules governing pilot certification and operations of a novel technology like poweredlift eVTOLs should be modernized to reflect the unique aspects of electrification and range. ... However, at this years summit, the mood had shifted toward cautious optimism for the release of the final SFAR. Theres great anticipation for the rule, which were told is coming in just a few weeks, said Kristie Greco Johnson, senior vice president of government affairs with the National Business Aviation Association NBAA. If the FAA can deliver the rule in just a few short weeks, itll be a major accomplishment for the agency. ... While Coes contends the final SFAR will be released in the next month, the FAA technically has until Dec. 16 to finalize the regulation, according to the FAA reauthorizaton bill. The same bill also mandated that a notice of proposed rulemaking NPRM for unmanned aerial systems UAS operating beyond visual line of sight BVLOS be issued by Sept. 16. However, the FAA missed that deadline, raising concerns about the SFARs timely release. There is broad consensus that the U.S. faces stiff competition from global players to lead in AAM. With first movers like Joby Aviation and Archer Aviation aiming for a 2025 commercialization of eVTOLs, the pressure is on the FAA to meet expectations.

They have more motors and more propellers not to mention the hinges that have to move to allow them to transition from vertical to horizontal flight. They still have to be trained to the standard that the FAA requires and since they are flying a vehicle that can fly like a helicopter or an airplane, they need to have training in both, something that is certainly not cheap. Directional drilling is fascinating. I worked the rigs for a few years in Canada and the technology they use is so cool. Theta gang is generally people who SELL options rather than buy them. You will often find references to people doing the wheel which is selling puts and when assigned, selling calls on the stock. If it gets assigned, they take that profit and then sell more cash secured puts with it. If all this terminology is too far out there for you, just look up the terms individually and it will start to make sense. I do not wheel, I just want to own PLTR long term. But in the short term, I profit off of the volatility of the stock by selling calls to peopel who are gambling that its going to go a lot higher in the near term. Today it was pressing 34 and I sold calls for 35 at the end of the week. Im betting it fades its gains by then. If not, then Ill be on the hook to have to sell the shares at 35, no matter what price it is. If its lower, then I keep the money the call buyers gave me for the option and the option will expire worthless.

OP is running a covered call strategy. By buying 100 shares of PLTR and pledging them as collateral for a sold call, OP makes money as time moves forward and generally makes money if the price of the stock remains steady or moves mildly up or down. The downside of the strategy is, if PLTR shares rally significantly, past his strike price, he will only make the premium of the sold calls and likely be assigned, essentially being forced to sell his shares below market price.

PLTR now owns 8.7% of Faraday Future, an EV startup according to a recent SEC filing 🤔

It's a smart move and has noting to do with EVs, but not for reasons many think.

Faraday Future initially agreed to pay Palantir for services rendered but could only pay part of that in cash. So, Palantir's taken shares in lieu of a write off. 

1. If Faraday’s financial situation improves, the shares received may increase in value, potentially providing Palantir with a better return than it would have received by writing off the debt to nil.

2. Depending on Palantir’s tax situation, accepting shares instead of writing off Faraday’s bad debt allows Palantir to potentially defer recognizing a loss until the shares are sold, which, in turn, helps Team Karp to manage tax liability more effectively.

Is this premium justified? I believe that paying a premium for a stock is justified only when the company offers something uniquely valuable or disruptive. In Palantir’s case, from my perspective there’s definitely something special. The company is a pure-play software provider, specializing in AI solutions for enterprises and government agencies. In CEO Alex Karp’s most recent letter to shareholders, he highlighted the “unrelenting wave of demand” from customers for production-ready AI systems, and Palantir is among the few companies that can meet that demand today.

Given these factors, I believe Palantir is uniquely positioned to capitalize on the trillion-dollar AI market and capture a significant share of the enterprise software sector, which is projected to reach about $790 billion by 2032.

It's pure manipulation by the MMers as they control it all.You can learn to use it to your benefit rather than complain about it,  How?  2 ways add knowing it was likely artificially kept down today, often you can save a couple% on purchase price by looking at maxpain and/or finviz.Second way is to write the 40 or higher calls knowing they will likely be successful pinning it to 40.I don't claim to be a wizard these are widely available simple tools.  Not like bollinger bands, candle sticks, CNBC used to have a guy on that prognosticated stock prices based on Astrology, I'm not kidding.  Some of the wiz bang chart guys have terms that sound like they are gymnastics terms.IMO pay attention to maxpain then look at open calls on your favorite stocks.  Usually puts are way less qty and don't have nearly the effect.Long PLTR common, JAN 2025 17's, JAN 2026 20's.

Here’s my quick debrief after today’s awesome close.  Muted LewZaz (credit to Dom for the censor workaround) need not reply, although you always do anyway, and do me the courtesy of muting me before we continue—I can’t stand the thought of you gollums getting any benefit from reading this.

What can we expect from here?  I view today as a big pressure relief valve.  There was probably many active managers with big unrealized gains who couldn’t exit quickly without cratering the price in the process of doing so.  Today gave them that opportunity with a tsunami of funds flows they could sell into.  Think of index funds like a sponge soaking up shares.  Unlike active funds, the shares soaked up today aren’t really trading positions anymore.  The index funds will only buy and sell now based on the capital flows of broad market (SP500) investors.  Perhaps the biggest benefit of this change in ownership, from active to passive, going forward will be the dampening of PLTR volatility. A very good thing.

It looks like most index funds successfully rebalanced today, and hopefully this means a good amount of looming sell pressure was quickly alleviated (again by giving them a tsunami of liquidity to sell into).  PLTR is in the major leagues now, which brings with it new class of well heeled investors.   The future looks bright longs.  Cheers 🍻

The SOLE purpose of index funds are to track the index as closely as possible (aka minimize tracking error). That means maintaining a fund composition that mirrors the index. PLTR goes into the index, PLTR goes into the index fund. Simple as that. Do not listen to anyone saying that managers have a choice, or are gonna wait for a better price. These are NOT active funds. The manager of an index fund is tasked with one thing only: mirror the index performance.  They do not care what the price of PLTR is, period. They just need to own it so that its performance is reflected in their fund just as it is in the index.

What you can expect starting on Monday from the more than 10 trillion dollars passively indexed to the SP500:  

Index funds typically acquire shares of a new company after it is officially added to the index. When a company is announced as a new constituent of the S&P 500, index funds tracking the S&P 500 will adjust their portfolios to include the new company. This adjustment usually occurs after the official inclusion date, aligning with the fund's objective to replicate the index as closely as possible.

The timing of these adjustments can vary slightly among different funds, but generally, they aim to minimize tracking error by purchasing shares around the time the company is officially part of the index. This ensures that the fund's performance continues to mirror that of the S&P 500 accurately.

Tens of billions of dollars have yet to purchase PLTR when it’s officially included in the SP500 on the 23rd.  This is not theoretical. That’s just icing on the cake.

A CEO who’s publicly declaring growth possibilities of 10-20x. Wanna argue that’s just hype? Okay. But he has more knowledge of the opportunity set ahead than we ever will and has more to lose if he misses the mark. If he didn’t expect to deliver on his remarks, then he’d moderate his enthusiasm so as to not over promise and under deliver.

Two major bubbles in 20 years suggest “markets have gotten more disconnected from reality over time,” Mr. Asness writes. And he sees little evidence that the disconnect is going away.Right now the value spread is still very high. Mr. Asness measures it a couple of ways, using simple price-to-book ratios in one example and a more wide-ranging set of valuation yardsticks in another, but the upshot is the same: The top 30 per cent of stocks are selling at unusually lofty prices compared to the bottom 30 per cent.Mr. Asness argues this top-heavy structure cannot be explained simply as the result of a boom in a handful of technology stocks. The phenomenon seems rooted in something more structural.He points to three possible candidates. The first is indexing. The widespread adoption of indexing strategies may have rendered the market insensitive to how cheap or expensive a stock is. The second is the impact of ultralow interest rates for much of the past 15 years. Maybe easy money has helped encourage a giddy, what-the-heck approach to valuing hot stocks.Then there is a third candidate, Mr. Asness’s favourite. This is not an endorsement.Mr. Trump recently stated that he supports reducing the top corporate income tax bracketfrom 21% to 15% in order to help companies like PLTR to compete strongly against foreigncompetitors. 7 years ago, Mr. Trump spearheaded reducing the rate from 35% to 21%.Ms. Harris proposes increasing the top corporate rate from 21% to 28%, a 25% increase inincome tax PLTR would have to pay instead of investing in it's growth.Mr. Trump wants to maintain the current long-term capital gains tax on sales of PLTR stockat 15% and 20% for higher earners.Ms. Harris proposes taxing capital gains taxes as ordinary earnings. So an investor in the 28% marginal income tax bracket would see in increase in capital gains taxes on PLTR stock sales from 15% to 28%, almost doubling the tax owed. Ms. Harris also proposes, with Mr. Biden,to impose the tax on "unrealized" gains, on PLTR stock that an investor owns but has not yetsold. The unrealized gain tax would be imposed on higher earners.Mr. Trump lowered personal income tax brackets across the board in 2017. Those reductions will "sunset" (end) in 2025 if they are not renewed. Mr. Trump wants to renew them. Ms. Harris avoids the subject, but Mr. Biden has expressed disdain for the 2017 reductions. The increased standard deduction would also sunset. If the brackets sunset and increase to the pre-2017 levels, so too would the cap-gains tax with Harris's proposal.

Inclusion in the S&P 500 offers several advantages:

1. **Increased Visibility**: Enhanced public profile and credibility.
2. **Attracting Investment**: More institutional investors are likely to invest, boosting stock demand.
3. **Liquidity**: Increased trading volume improves stock liquidity.
4. **Benchmarking**: Companies can use the index as a performance benchmark.
5. **Employee Morale**: Can boost employee confidence and retention, especially if stock options are involved.
6. **Market Perception**: Often seen as a mark of stability and financial health. 

Overall, it can lead to improved financial performance and shareholder value.

Inclusion in the S&P 500 offers several advantages:

1. **Increased Visibility**: Enhanced public profile and credibility.
2. **Attracting Investment**: More institutional investors are likely to invest, boosting stock demand.
3. **Liquidity**: Increased trading volume improves stock liquidity.
4. **Benchmarking**: Companies can use the index as a performance benchmark.
5. **Employee Morale**: Can boost employee confidence and retention, especially if stock options are involved.
6. **Market Perception**: Often seen as a mark of stability and financial health. 

Overall, it will lead to improved financial performance and shareholder value.

The problem may lie with its mammoth share count. Palantir's share count is fairly high with more than 2.2 billion shares outstanding. Even though the company generated a strong 20% profit margin and net income totaled $134.1 million this past quarter, that still equates to a per-share profit of just $0.06 when you divide that profit by all those shares.

That, in turn, hurts the stock's valuation. If the stock is trading at around $29 and the company's annual earnings per share is just $0.17, investors are paying a massive price-to-earnings multiple of 170. Even based on revenue, the stock is trading at a multiple of 29. For my fellow long-term Trader Buds...'THE RULE OF 40'.   In my research, I discovered a straightforward yet widely accepted formula to gauge the short- to medium-term profitability of a SaaS company. This is relevant for the short to medium term as these metrics can shift with each quarterly earnings report. (even month[y)   The 'Rule of 40' for SaaS companies is an uncomplicated financial metric that combines just two figures: revenue growth and profit margin. It serves as a quick heuristic to assess the health and appeal of a SaaS business.  To apply it, simply add the two numbers together; a total of 40 is the benchmark.Any number above this is considered a bonus.   For instance, CRM's score is 46, while PLTR's is an impressive 64, indicating that PLTR is significantly outperforming.             Hope this helps Guys.
